No change in my forecast. Breaking news confirms my 1% "yes" forecast previously. Katherine Tai confirmed as U.S. Trade Representative today. On the strategic side, the current US administration will be more amenable to new trade agreements with China (https://www.eastasiaforum.org/2021/02/15/will-bidens-america-change-course-on-china-and-trade/). However, the phase 1 agreement signed by the Trump 'failed' because China went slow with the purchase commitments (https://www.piie.com/blogs/trade-and-investment-policy-watch/anatomy-flop-why-trumps-us-china-phase-one-trade-deal-fell). Tactically, it will take a long time for any new trade agreements for the following reasons: Biden's trade representative, Katherine Tai still awaits Senate confirmation. Her statement is China must deliver phase 1 commitments. This will delay start of any negotiation process. Hence, July is too soon to see any agreement. From the Chinese perspective, one should also note that China has concluded a comprehensive trade deal with EU.

President-elect Biden will not have enough time to renegotiate with China since a large chunk of his coming months of presidency will be focused on transition, the virus, and reunification of the divided country. Moreover, the situation is not favorable economically for the US to coerce China into a favorable agreement.

While I anticipate a rollback of Trump admin protectionism, a trade agreement is unlikely in this timeframe. Unlikely due to: - US domestic political costs in dealing with China favorably - US geopolitical fears of a rising China - Bureaucratic slowness in negotiating any given trade deal (considering US, China, recent EU deal) - Time lost in Biden onboarding/acclimation process (1-3 months will be lost in friction before anything like this would be approached) - If Biden admin does focus on China trade, initial efforts will be on rolling back Trump "trade war" efforts (versus a new deal)

With these variables and complexities at play, it makes the prospects of a US-Sino trade deal to come about within 6 months of Biden taking office even more remote.
